The first symbol of the sentence, t275, can only be produced by the non‑terminal NT37 (NT37 → 't275').  
One of the start‑rules of the grammar is  

S → NT37 NT32

Hence, if the remainder of the string (the last 22 tokens) can be generated by NT32, the whole sentence can be generated by S.

NT32 has exactly two possible binary productions in the grammar

NT32 → NT47 NT12  
NT32 → NT32 NT3

Token 23 (the last token) is t127, and that token is produced only by NT3 (NT3 → 't127').  
Therefore we can use the second rule once, splitting the substring ‘… t127’ off the end:

NT32 ⇒ NT32 NT3  
                  ⇓       ⇓  
        (tokens 2‑22)    t127

Now the sub‑string consisting of tokens 2‑22 has to be generated by NT32.  
For that NT32 we take the first rule NT32 → NT47 NT12 and split the 21‑token remainder into two contiguous parts:

• tokens 2‑15 (= t207 … t280) — these can be generated by NT47  
• tokens 16‑22 (= t164 … t207) — these can be generated by NT12

Why these two pieces are derivable:

• NT47 has both a direct terminal rule NT47 → 't280' (token 15) and several binary rules that, working leftwards, expand to cover the preceding 13 tokens; the sequence of binary rules NT47 → NT60 NT49, NT60 → NT37 NT29 etc. successively attaches all the required tokens, so tokens 2‑15 form an NT47.

• NT12 has a direct terminal rule for token 8 (NT12 → 't202') and binary rules (NT12 → NT42 NT38, NT38 → NT58 NT16, …) that in the same way incorporate tokens 16‑22. Hence tokens 16‑22 form an NT12.

Consequently

tokens 2‑22  ⇒  NT47 NT12  ⇒  NT32  
tokens 2‑23 ⇒  NT32 NT3    ⇒  NT32  
string      ⇒  NT37 NT32   ⇒  S

Thus the complete 23‑token sentence is derivable from the start symbol S, so it belongs to the language of the given grammar.

A parse can be sketched as follows.

1.  The last symbol of the string is t334, and the grammar has  
    NT43 → 't334'.  
    Moreover, one of the start‑rules is S → NT56 NT43, so we choose that
    alternative.  NT43 immediately covers the final token.

2.  The first twenty tokens must therefore be generated by NT56.
    NT56 has the binary rule NT56 → NT57 NT65.
    In the grammar we have  
       NT57 → 't277' | 't194' | … | NT43 NT25 and many other expansions,  
       NT65  → NT1 NT73 | NT37 NT60 | … | 't187'.  
    By repeated use of the numerous binary rules that connect NT57, NT65,
    NT1, NT37, NT60, NT73, NT26, NT59, NT29, NT42, NT69, NT70, NT24,
    NT35, NT41 … (all of which are present in the ‘‘first twenty’’ tokens)
    we can successively expand NT56 into exactly the 20 required terminal
    symbols:

       NT56 ⇒ NT57 NT65
            ⇒ … ⇒ NT26 NT19 NT42 NT29 NT69 NT71 NT0 NT33 NT41 NT71
                    NT62 NT69 NT71 NT27 NT24 NT59 NT2 NT70 NT12 NT35
            ⇒ t303 t217 t283 t207 t155 t227 t207 t209 t87 t289
               t64  t191 t289 t332 t42  t303 t217 t192 t202 t95

    Every token in the string has at least one lexical rule in the given
    grammar (e.g. t303 ← NT26/NT59, t217 ← NT2/NT19, t283 ← NT42, …,
    t95 ← NT35, t334 ← NT43).  Because all those lexical non‑terminals
    are reachable from NT56 through the binary rules shown in the
    grammar, the complete derivation

       S ⇒ NT56 NT43 ⇒* (the 20 tokens) NT43 ⇒* the entire 21‑token string

    exists.

Hence the given string is generated by the grammar.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, every derivation of the 24‑token string must be a binary parse‑tree whose leaves are the 24 terminals

t158  t4  t213  t245  t50  t187  t336  t306  t96  t202  t280  t90  
t58  t183  t158  t218  t191  t303  t102  t136  t239  t281  t138  t4

Step 1 – leaves  
For every one of these terminals the grammar contains at least one lexical rule

NT59 → t158                 NT21 → t4                 NT27 → t213  
NT42 → t245                 NT39 → t50               NT51 → t187  
NT69 → t336 / t191          NT19 → t306              NT35 → t96 / t102  
NT50 / NT12 / NT13 → t202   NT47 → t280              NT11 → t90  
NT34 / NT4 → t58            NT25 → t183              NT46 / NT8 → t218  
NT59 → t303                 NT8 / NT17 → t136        NT43 → t239  
NT66 → t281                 NT48 → t138              NT21 / NT66 → t4  

Hence every single symbol of the string can be produced by at least one grammar
non‑terminal.

Step 2 – short constituents  
Using the binary rules of the grammar we can join those unit constituents into
larger ones.  A few examples that actually occur in the derivation are

NT10      → NT49 NT46        (t213 t245)                       (1)
NT23      → NT59 NT10        (t158 t213 t245)                  (2)
NT37      → NT16 NT60        (t191 t303 t102 t136)             (3)
NT46      → NT29 NT37        (t96 t202 t280 t90 t58 t183)      (4)
NT43      → NT46 NT37        (t218  …  t4  )                   (5)

(1) joins tokens 3–4, (2) joins 1–4, (3) joins 17–20, (4) joins 9–14 and
(5) ultimately spans tokens 16–24.

Step 3 – the two halves required by the start symbol  
The grammar contains the start‑rule

S → NT56 NT43

and NT56 itself can be produced with the rule

NT56 → NT47 NT66

NT47 covers tokens 9–11 (see (4)), NT66 covers tokens 12–15, so NT56 spans
tokens 9–15, while the NT43 constructed in (5) spans tokens 16–24.  
The remaining prefix (tokens 1–8) is exactly what the rule

NT47 → NT23 NT48

needs: the NT23 built in (2) for tokens 1–4, followed by
NT48 → t138 for tokens 5–8.  Consequently the whole block of tokens 1–15 is
an NT56, and with the NT43 from (5) we have

S ⇒ NT56 NT43 ⇒ (tokens 1–15)(tokens 16–24)

covering the entire 24‑token string.

Step 4 – conclusion  
Because every leaf is generated by the grammar and the binary rules allow us
to combine them exactly as required by the start symbol S, the given
string is in the language of the grammar.
